main event: Multiple sightings of high-speed, fusiform-shaped objects heading north in Rehoboth Beach, Delaware, between September 1944 and June 1947.
interesting points: The objects were estimated to be traveling at speeds ranging from 10,000 to 24,000 mph.
The observer was a civilian pilot with 9 years of experience.
This was the second such object the observer had seen, with a previous sighting in December 1946.
The report suggests the possibility that the observed objects were 'Skyhook' or 'Far-Go' missiles from the Applied Physics Laboratory of Johns Hopkins University.
The document mentions that positive identification could be made if the exact day and hour of observation were known.
